<subSubSection id="62D36507FFC1A21CFCF08D57304806B4" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="140" pageId="7" pageNumber="139" type="description">
<paragraph id="2A76368CFFC1A21CFCF08D57304806B4" blockId="7.[806,1421,1820,1903]" lastBlockId="8.[164,779,198,648]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="140" pageId="7" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis id="18BDEA9EFFC1A213FCF08D573289030D" box="[806,950,1820,1841]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="139">Occurrences:</emphasis>
Only known from the River Bend Formation in 
<collectingRegion id="E80DF86EFFC1A213FC7E8D713562036C" box="[936,1117,1850,1872]" country="United States of America" name="North Carolina" pageId="7" pageNumber="139">North Carolina</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingCountry id="52DE761CFFC1A213FBA78D713597036C" box="[1137,1192,1850,1872]" name="United States of America" pageId="7" pageNumber="139">USA</collectingCountry>
) possibly dated as Middle–Late Oligocene (
<bibRefCitation id="4E584B7DFFC1A213FBE98D1235FB0353" author="Ward LW" box="[1087,1220,1881,1903]" pageId="7" pageNumber="139" pagination="78" refId="ref19647" refString="Ward LW. 1985. Stratigraphy and characteristic molluscs of the Pamunkey Group (Lower Tertiary) and the Old Church Formation of the Chesapeake Group - Virginia Coastal plain. U. S. Geological Survey, Professional Paper, 1346: IV + 78 S. Washington." type="journal article" year="1985">
Ward, 
<quantity id="ED319B69FFC1A213FB5B8D1235FB0353" box="[1165,1220,1881,1903]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0419" pageId="7" pageNumber="139" unit="in" value="1985.0">1985</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="4E584B7DFFC1A213FB3A8D1234BE0353" author="Muller A" box="[1260,1409,1881,1903]" pageId="7" pageNumber="139" pagination="1 - 360" refId="ref18584" refString="Muller A. 1999. Ichthyofaunen aus dem atlantischen Tertiar der USA. Leipziger Geowissenschaften 9 - 10: 1 - 360." type="journal article" year="1999">Müller, 1999</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="18BDEA9EFFCEA21CFF728A8D303004E7" box="[164,271,198,219]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="140">Remarks:</emphasis>
Teeth are broken (no root thoroughly preserved) but their morphologies are unusual, having a labiolingually compressed root, a high crown with an inclined upper labial face that displays a strongly ornamented enamel (except in its apical part) with numerous grooves, at least in adult specimens (
<bibRefCitation id="4E584B7DFFCEA21CFD1A8B1431E105AF" author="Case GR" pageId="8" pageNumber="140" pagination="75 - 103" refId="ref17206" refString="Case GR. 1980. A selachian fauna from the Trent Formation, Lower Miocene (Aquitanian) of Eastern North Carolina. Palaeontographica, Abteilung A 171: 75 - 103." type="journal article" year="1980">Case, 1980</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 10, fig. 1), and an irregular transversal crest. 
<bibRefCitation id="4E584B7DFFCEA21CFF728BD730E0058E" author="Cicimurri DJ &amp; Knight JL" box="[164,479,412,434]" pageId="8" pageNumber="140" pagination="627 - 647" refId="ref17375" refString="Cicimurri DJ, Knight JL. 2009. Late Oligocene sharks and rays from the Chandler Bridge Formation, Dorchester County, South Carolina, USA. Acta Palaeontologica Polonica 54: 627 - 647." type="journal article" year="2009">Cicimurri &amp; Knight (2009)</bibRefCitation>
considered that only the 
<typeStatus id="F572882EFFCEA21CFF728BF0303A05ED" box="[164,261,443,465]" pageId="8" pageNumber="140">holotype</typeStatus>
(large specimen) is referable to 
<taxonomicName id="EDC94D0FFFCEA21CFD628BF0323405EC" authorityName="RAFINESQUE" authorityYear="1810" box="[692,779,443,464]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Myliobatidae" genus="Mobula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="140" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="18BDEA9EFFCEA21CFD628BF0323405EC" box="[692,779,443,464]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="140">Mobula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
whereas the 
<typeStatus id="F572882EFFCEA21CFE9D8B91308C05D3" box="[331,435,474,495]" pageId="8" pageNumber="140">paratype</typeStatus>
, nearly two times smaller, belongs to the dubious genus † 
<taxonomicName id="EDC94D0FFFCEA21CFDC68BB333A20631" authorityName="Pfeil" authorityYear="1981" box="[528,669,504,525]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Mobulidae" genus="Paramobula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="140" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="18BDEA9EFFCEA21CFDC68BB333A20631" box="[528,669,504,525]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="140">Paramobula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Without additional evidence beyond size, we disagree with such splitting and consider that both the 
<typeStatus id="F572882EFFCEA21CFDAE887E33E60677" box="[632,729,565,587]" pageId="8" pageNumber="140">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus id="F572882EFFCEA21CFF72881F30350655" box="[164,266,596,617]" pageId="8" pageNumber="140">paratype</typeStatus>
belong to the same species (adult and juvenile, respectively).
</paragraph>
